WEBVTT

00:00:00.480 --> 00:00:02.960
Hey teachers, I don't know if you feel

00:00:02.960 --> 00:00:05.600
the same as I do, but teaching writing

00:00:05.600 --> 00:00:08.240
is not my cup of tea. So, here are a

00:00:08.240 --> 00:00:10.000
couple of writing games and activities

00:00:10.000 --> 00:00:13.800
that might help.

00:00:37.120 --> 00:00:39.440
Okay, the activities I'm sharing with

00:00:39.440 --> 00:00:41.520
you in this video aren't for a

00:00:41.520 --> 00:00:44.480
particular writing skill or lesson. So,

00:00:44.480 --> 00:00:46.399
feel free to apply them to whatever

00:00:46.399 --> 00:00:48.800
lesson you find suitable. Let's call the

00:00:48.800 --> 00:00:52.640
first activity pass or switch or freeze.

00:00:52.640 --> 00:00:54.320
I'm sorry, I couldn't make up my mind.

00:00:54.320 --> 00:00:56.399
This activity would work as a great

00:00:56.399 --> 00:00:58.800
warm-up or practice. My lesson was about

00:00:58.800 --> 00:01:01.199
the cause and effect essay, and I wanted

00:01:01.199 --> 00:01:04.000
them to brainstorm some ideas in an

00:01:04.000 --> 00:01:06.479
untraditional way before they start

00:01:06.479 --> 00:01:09.119
writing. So, I gave each student a paper

00:01:09.119 --> 00:01:11.760
with a particular topic like these ones.

00:01:11.760 --> 00:01:14.240
If you have a large class, students can

00:01:14.240 --> 00:01:17.040
work in pairs or can work in groups.

00:01:17.040 --> 00:01:19.040
Then I explained that they have to write

00:01:19.040 --> 00:01:21.600
down one single cause or effect

00:01:21.600 --> 00:01:23.759
depending on their cards and pass it to

00:01:23.759 --> 00:01:26.320
the student next to them. And on the new

00:01:26.320 --> 00:01:28.400
card they will do the same. The cards

00:01:28.400 --> 00:01:30.960
kept moving from one student to another

00:01:30.960 --> 00:01:33.280
till we got you know enough ideas. I

00:01:33.280 --> 00:01:35.200
enjoyed this activity and I guess my

00:01:35.200 --> 00:01:37.520
student enjoyed it too because it

00:01:37.520 --> 00:01:39.520
encourages them to stay focused on

00:01:39.520 --> 00:01:42.079
different topics. So it wasn't boring at

00:01:42.079 --> 00:01:44.479
all because writing can be boring. It

00:01:44.479 --> 00:01:46.320
also lets them compare their answers

00:01:46.320 --> 00:01:48.240
with their peers which makes them get

00:01:48.240 --> 00:01:50.560
more perspectives and all of that

00:01:50.560 --> 00:01:52.720
happened in a fun engaging way. I tried

00:01:52.720 --> 00:01:54.560
the same activity but with a different

00:01:54.560 --> 00:01:56.720
topic. I was teaching the students how

00:01:56.720 --> 00:01:59.439
to write a formal email and I used this

00:01:59.439 --> 00:02:01.360
activity to make them memorize the

00:02:01.360 --> 00:02:03.680
elements they should include. So I put

00:02:03.680 --> 00:02:06.479
them into groups and I gave each group a

00:02:06.479 --> 00:02:08.720
couple of papers like these and I told

00:02:08.720 --> 00:02:11.039
them to write a formal email following

00:02:11.039 --> 00:02:13.440
the structure they already learned. you

00:02:13.440 --> 00:02:15.760
know, starting with a good subject line,

00:02:15.760 --> 00:02:18.400
then greeting, then the purpose, and all

00:02:18.400 --> 00:02:20.800
of the good stuff. Here, they had to pay

00:02:20.800 --> 00:02:22.959
attention to both the structure of the

00:02:22.959 --> 00:02:25.280
email and the order of the elements.

00:02:25.280 --> 00:02:27.840
With another group, we had the narrative

00:02:27.840 --> 00:02:29.920
essay. I set up the context of the

00:02:29.920 --> 00:02:32.640
essay, a time that you experienced

00:02:32.640 --> 00:02:35.440
something truly frightening. We worked

00:02:35.440 --> 00:02:38.160
in pairs, so every pair had a large

00:02:38.160 --> 00:02:40.640
piece of paper. And I told them, "Now

00:02:40.640 --> 00:02:42.800
you're going to start narrating your

00:02:42.800 --> 00:02:45.680
spooky story, but as you write it, at

00:02:45.680 --> 00:02:47.440
some point you will hear me say,

00:02:47.440 --> 00:02:50.080
"Freeze." And when I say freeze, even if

00:02:50.080 --> 00:02:52.239
you're in the middle of a word or in the

00:02:52.239 --> 00:02:54.959
middle of a sentence, you stop writing

00:02:54.959 --> 00:02:57.599
and transfer your paper to the pair next

00:02:57.599 --> 00:02:59.840
to you. The students began to write. I

00:02:59.840 --> 00:03:01.280
checked that everyone has written

00:03:01.280 --> 00:03:03.200
something before I said freeze for the

00:03:03.200 --> 00:03:05.280
first time. Then I was like, "Freeze."

00:03:05.280 --> 00:03:07.360
papers were transferred to the next two

00:03:07.360 --> 00:03:09.760
group so that everyone's working with

00:03:09.760 --> 00:03:11.840
another piece of paper with a different

00:03:11.840 --> 00:03:13.760
story on it. The students finished up

00:03:13.760 --> 00:03:16.159
their stories. I gave them some time to

00:03:16.159 --> 00:03:18.400
read, correct, and improve them. And

00:03:18.400 --> 00:03:20.720
honestly, all the stories deserved an

00:03:20.720 --> 00:03:23.360
Oscar. Moving on to the second activity,

00:03:23.360 --> 00:03:26.400
writing postcards. Using postcards in

00:03:26.400 --> 00:03:29.200
class can be a motivating writing task

00:03:29.200 --> 00:03:32.239
and it adds a level of stimulation for

00:03:32.239 --> 00:03:34.480
the students. I have seen this activity

00:03:34.480 --> 00:03:37.200
online and my students really loved it

00:03:37.200 --> 00:03:39.360
since they don't have to write too much

00:03:39.360 --> 00:03:41.680
and I loved it because it involves a

00:03:41.680 --> 00:03:43.599
certain level of communication and

00:03:43.599 --> 00:03:45.840
imagination which I'm personally fond

00:03:45.840 --> 00:03:48.799
of. If you can get a stack of postcards

00:03:48.799 --> 00:03:50.879
that's awesome. But if you don't have

00:03:50.879 --> 00:03:53.280
any, you could do just like me and print

00:03:53.280 --> 00:03:55.840
them on papers or cards and add some

00:03:55.840 --> 00:03:58.159
lovely pictures. Anyway, if you're

00:03:58.159 --> 00:04:00.720
teaching kids, I recommend getting them

00:04:00.720 --> 00:04:03.280
to draw their own pictures instead of

00:04:03.280 --> 00:04:05.680
printing them out. Ask them to write a

00:04:05.680 --> 00:04:08.720
postcard to a friend telling them about

00:04:08.720 --> 00:04:11.519
their imaginary holiday and how the

00:04:11.519 --> 00:04:13.519
picture relates to it. You can

00:04:13.519 --> 00:04:15.519
absolutely choose a different context.

00:04:15.519 --> 00:04:17.519
Once they have written the cards, some

00:04:17.519 --> 00:04:19.759
of the students read it out loud and at

00:04:19.759 --> 00:04:22.479
the end I collect it and check them up

00:04:22.479 --> 00:04:24.400
for them. I think I was teaching

00:04:24.400 --> 00:04:27.600
fragments and run on sentences and saw

00:04:27.600 --> 00:04:30.240
what errors were made and prepared a

00:04:30.240 --> 00:04:33.360
correction slot for the next class.

00:04:33.360 --> 00:04:35.040
That's pretty it. Thank you for

00:04:35.040 --> 00:04:38.840
watching, awesome teachers.
